  "prompt": "What is the meaning of Ishraq in Islam?",
  "response": "In Islam, **Ishraq** (\u0625\u0634\u0631\u0627\u0642) refers to the **voluntary prayer** performed shortly after sunrise. The word itself means \"radiance\" or \"illumination,\" symbolizing the light and spiritual awakening associated with this time of day. It is considered a highly meritorious act.\n\n- **Timing**: Ishraq prayer is offered after the sun has risen fully and has reached the height of a spear (approximately 15-20 minutes after sunrise).\n- **Rakats**: It typically consists of **2 rakats** (units of prayer), though some scholars recommend 4 rakats.\n- **Significance**: It is regarded as a means of gaining blessings, spiritual enlightenment, and the reward of performing Hajj and Umrah, as mentioned in some hadiths.\n- **Hadith Reference**: The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) is reported to have said: \"Whoever prays Fajr in congregation, then sits remembering Allah until the sun rises, then prays two rakats, will have a reward like that of Hajj and Umrah, complete, complete, complete.\" (Tirmidhi)\n\nPerforming Ishraq prayer reflects a commitment to starting the day with gratitude, mindfulness, and connection to Allah. It is not obligatory but is highly recommended as a form of **nafl (voluntary) worship**.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
